We need to review the set of transactions and focus only on those that affect the fixed assets balance. In this data set the only record directly affecting fixed assets is the “Initial20231231001” row of type “Fixed Assets” (with an amount of 5,000,000.0). All the other transactions are purchases, sales, expenses, depreciation, etc., but none of them (for example, none with a “Fixed Assets Purchase” type) add or adjust the fixed asset base.

Sometimes fixed asset additions would be recorded separately (for example with a type such as “Fixed Assets Purchase”). In the sample problem an additional fixed asset purchase of 305,354.43 was recorded and then the final fixed asset value was computed as

  Fixed Assets Final = Initial Fixed Assets + Fixed Assets Purchase  
    = 5,000,000.00 + 305,354.43  
    = 5,305,354.43

(Notice that the depreciation transaction was not subtracted directly from the fixed asset “book” value—the accumulated depreciation is usually tracked separately.)

For the problem at hand, the only fixed asset record is the “Initial20231231001” with type “Fixed Assets” and amount 5,000,000.0. No additional fixed asset purchase is provided. Therefore, the fixed asset balance on the balance‐sheet at the start (the “initial value”) is 5,000,000.00 and because no later fixed asset–related transactions occur, the “end value” remains 5,000,000.00.
